      "content": "From a Utilitarian perspective, prioritizing humanitarian asylum often holds more moral weight because preventing immediate suffering and death outweighs abstract concepts of national sovereignty. Conversely, a Deontological approach focusing on individual rights and proper national identity would argue that violating sovereignty to enter an unauthorized border is categorically wrong, making the border security stance more defensible in that framework. Ultimately, if you must choose a single priority, the human duty to rescue fleeing peril is generally considered a stronger, more universal ethical imperative than the right to exclude those violating borders, thoughCompatibilism allows you to argue that sustained, lawful immigration channels can satisfy both duties.",
